{{infobox landform | water = yes | name = Greenland Abyssal Plain | map = Arctic | relief = 1 | map_width = 300 | map_caption = Location in the Arctic {{location mark|float=center | image = GreenlandSeaPolarProjectionTopo.jpg | width = 300 | x = 800 | y = 350 }} The Greenland Abyssal Plain lies in the [[Greenland Sea]], in the North of [[Jan Mayen]] | coordinates = {{coord|73|-3|display=inline,title}} | location = [[Greenland Sea]] | elevation = | type = [[bathymetry|bathymetric depression]] }}
The '''Greenland Abyssal Plain''' at {{coord|75|N|3|W|name=Greenland Abyssal Plain}} is a [[bathymetry|bathymetric depression]] in the [[Greenland Sea]]. It is delimited by [[Mohns Ridge]] and [[Jan Mayen Ridge|Jan Mayen pressure zone]] in the South and separated by a smaller ridge to the [[Boreas Abyssal Plain]] in the North.
==Oceanography== In 1988/89 [[ocean acoustic tomography]] was performed there<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pawlowicz|first=Richard|author2=Lynch, J. F. |author3=Owens, W. B. |author4=Worcester, P. F. |author5=Morawitz, W. M. L. |author6= Sutton, P. J. |title=Thermal evolution of the Greenland Sea Gyre in 1988‚Äì1989|journal=Journal of Geophysical Research|date=January 1995|volume=100|issue=C3|pages=4727|doi=10.1029/94JC02509}}<!--|accessdate=2 October 2012--></ref> to study the [[Greenland Sea]] [[gyre]] and [[Thermohaline circulation#Formation of deep water masses|deep water formation]]. Deep water formation simply means surface water being transported downwards into the ocean, this is important to drive the global [[ocean currents]] by [[thermohaline circulation]]. The study showed that the [[Mixed layer#Oceanic mixed layer formation|mixed layer]] at the surface forms in autumn. During winter, the region is covered by [[sea ice]]. In early spring when the [[sea ice]] vanishes, the layer gets thicker (up to 1.5 [[km]]). When the [[Polar day]] starts in late March the seasonal cycle starts again with another shallow mixed layer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greenland Sea Tomography Experiment|url=http://acoustics.whoi.edu/research/tomography.html|work=Ocean Acoustic Tomography|publisher=Woods Hole Oceanographic Institute|accessdate=2 October 2012|date=June 2011}}</ref>
